    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "thanks. that makes sense. i also heard there's a difference between that and caramelization? can you explain the distinction between the two so i don't mix them up on the test?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Certainly! Think of the Maillard reaction as the grand ball of flavors, where proteins and sugars mingle in a complex dance, creating a rich tapestry of taste and aroma. It occurs at higher temperatures, typically above 140 degrees Celsius (284 degrees Fahrenheit). On the other hand, caramelization is like a solo performance by sugars, where they break down and form new flavors and colors at lower temperatures, usually between 160 to 180 degrees Celsius (320 to 356 degrees Fahrenheit). So, while both are about sugars, the Maillard reaction involves proteins and amino acids, and caramelization is all about sugars. Keep these two distinct performances in mind, and you'll be a maestro in the kitchen of chemistry!",
